1
00:00:21,673 --> 00:00:24,459
Woman on P.A.: 
Manager to check stand two 
for check approval.

2
00:00:24,502 --> 00:00:26,809
Yeah, check the label.

3
00:00:31,118 --> 00:00:32,641
 [ chatter ]

4
00:00:35,992 --> 00:00:38,168
Woman on P.A.: 
Cleanup on aisle two.

5
00:01:00,712 --> 00:01:02,801
Woman's voice: 
Wait a minute.

6
00:01:02,845 --> 00:01:05,108
 I see somebody I know.

7
00:01:09,982 --> 00:01:11,071
No.

8
00:01:17,381 --> 00:01:20,776
 [ chatter on P.A. ]

9
00:01:27,174 --> 00:01:29,132
Woman's voice: 
Do you know me?

10
00:01:29,176 --> 00:01:31,352
 Do you know me?

11
00:01:45,017 --> 00:01:47,368
 [ horn honks ]

12
00:01:47,411 --> 00:01:49,196
Okay, don't panic.

13
00:01:50,893 --> 00:01:52,634
Okay.

14
00:01:52,677 --> 00:01:54,636
My name is...

15
00:01:54,679 --> 00:01:56,812
My name is...

16
00:01:56,855 --> 00:01:59,423
Oh, my God.

17
00:01:59,467 --> 00:02:01,382
Oh, my God.

18
00:02:04,950 --> 00:02:07,475
 [ dog barking ]

19
00:02:07,518 --> 00:02:09,999
 Could this be my house,

20
00:02:10,042 --> 00:02:12,088
 my neighborhood?

21
00:02:23,099 --> 00:02:25,536
 [ phone rings ]

22
00:02:25,580 --> 00:02:27,625
- [ police radio chatter ]
- Woman's voice: Someone 
will help me.

23
00:02:27,669 --> 00:02:29,453
 Someone will find me.

24
00:02:38,288 --> 00:02:40,812
[ crying ]

25
00:02:40,856 --> 00:02:42,814
Honey,
have a sandwich.

26
00:02:42,858 --> 00:02:44,816
Oh, honey.

27
00:02:44,860 --> 00:02:47,558
Look, look,
that's your sandwich.

28
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:52,128
 Do I have a child?

29
00:02:53,825 --> 00:02:55,436
 Am I married?

30
00:03:10,625 --> 00:03:13,149
 Oh, my God.

31
00:03:21,549 --> 00:03:23,725
 [ phone ringing ]

32
00:03:25,640 --> 00:03:28,469
Woman: 
Jesus, stop it. 
Daddy's checking in.

33
00:03:28,512 --> 00:03:30,471
Child: 
But I want a burger. 
Cheeseburger and fries.

34
00:03:30,514 --> 00:03:33,169
Woman: 
You heard what I said. 
Now please be quiet.

35
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:35,867
 When we get up to the room, 
I'll order you something 
nutritious for a change.

36
00:03:35,911 --> 00:03:37,608
- But a burger's better.
- Jason, that's it.

37
00:03:37,652 --> 00:03:39,436
- You eat them
and so does Dad.
- Stop it

38
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:41,221
 or you'll have nothing 
to eat at all.

39
00:03:41,264 --> 00:03:42,961
Enjoy your stay.

40
00:03:47,314 --> 00:03:49,054
I'd like a room.

41
00:03:49,098 --> 00:03:50,752
I don't have
a reservation.

42
00:03:50,795 --> 00:03:52,754
Uh, I had
a change of plans.

43
00:03:52,797 --> 00:03:54,451
Man: 
Uh, how many 
in your party?

44
00:03:54,495 --> 00:03:56,410
No party, just me.

45
00:03:56,453 --> 00:03:58,150
- [ phone ringing ]
- Single, then.

46
00:03:58,194 --> 00:03:59,717
And how many nights?

47
00:03:59,761 --> 00:04:03,460
Um, one-- two, I--

48
00:04:03,504 --> 00:04:06,507
well, it just--
it just depends on
how my day goes.

49
00:04:07,856 --> 00:04:09,727
I think
we can handle that.

50
00:04:09,771 --> 00:04:13,601
- May I have your credit card?
- No, I don't have it with me.

51
00:04:13,644 --> 00:04:15,167
I told you I had
a change of plans.

52
00:04:15,211 --> 00:04:18,083
But that's no problem.
I can pay in cash.

53
00:04:18,127 --> 00:04:20,912
- How much is the room?
- 280 a night.

54
00:04:20,956 --> 00:04:23,959
It's our policy to take
a credit card imprint

55
00:04:24,002 --> 00:04:25,569
in case there are
other charges.

56
00:04:25,613 --> 00:04:27,267
Sir, are you telling me

57
00:04:27,310 --> 00:04:28,877
that the only way a person
can register in this hotel

58
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:30,879
is if they don'thave
the money to pay for it?

59
00:04:30,922 --> 00:04:33,229
Or is this policy reserved
just for women?

60
00:04:33,273 --> 00:04:35,710
I never suggested that,
ma'am. I--

61
00:04:35,753 --> 00:04:37,842
I know you didn't mean
to suggest that.

62
00:04:37,886 --> 00:04:40,367
I understand your concern

63
00:04:40,410 --> 00:04:41,977
and this is
a peculiar situation.

64
00:04:42,020 --> 00:04:43,326
It will be
straightened out

65
00:04:43,370 --> 00:04:45,328
as soon as my driver arrives
with my luggage

66
00:04:45,372 --> 00:04:46,677
and my briefcase.

67
00:04:50,812 --> 00:04:52,161
[ sighs ]

68
00:05:32,375 --> 00:05:34,725
Oh, God.

69
00:05:34,769 --> 00:05:36,771
[ gasps ]

70
00:06:03,624 --> 00:06:05,365
 [ water running ]

71
00:06:21,076 --> 00:06:22,947
- [ knob squeaks ]
- [ water shuts off ]

72
00:06:46,014 --> 00:06:48,233
Woman's voice: 
There's so much.

73
00:06:51,846 --> 00:06:53,325
 What's this?

74
00:06:57,678 --> 00:06:59,462
 Today.

75
00:06:59,506 --> 00:07:02,117
Pat Rutherford.

76
00:07:06,513 --> 00:07:10,255
 [ siren blaring 
in distance ]

77
00:07:22,703 --> 00:07:24,095
[ sighs ]

78
00:07:38,545 --> 00:07:40,329
Woman's voice: 
Pat Rutherford.

79
00:07:40,372 --> 00:07:42,374
 Man, woman? 
Come on.

80
00:07:42,418 --> 00:07:44,986
 Come on, 
give me something.

81
00:07:45,029 --> 00:07:46,378
 Give me anything.

82
00:07:49,599 --> 00:07:51,383
Can I help you
find something?

83
00:07:51,427 --> 00:07:54,648
Um, everything.
[ chuckles ]

84
00:07:57,259 --> 00:08:00,480
Woman's voice: 
Tailored. Looks all right, 
I guess.

85
00:08:05,572 --> 00:08:08,966
That'll be 489.63.

86
00:08:12,274 --> 00:08:13,841
I haven't seen that
in a while.

87
00:08:13,884 --> 00:08:16,104
I robbed a bank.

88
00:08:16,147 --> 00:08:19,150
Announcer: 
This is the final 
boarding call.

89
00:08:21,457 --> 00:08:22,937
Announcer: 
Your attention, please.

90
00:08:22,980 --> 00:08:25,200
 Southbound track-- 
Costa Mesa,

91
00:08:25,243 --> 00:08:28,116
 San Juan Capistrano, 
and San Diego--

92
00:08:28,159 --> 00:08:31,206
 is ready for boarding 
at gate number seven.

93
00:08:37,560 --> 00:08:41,216
I need to, uh,
talk to someone.

94
00:08:41,259 --> 00:08:43,305
 [ phone ringing ]

95
00:08:43,348 --> 00:08:45,525
Hi, I'm Dr. Melloff.

96
00:08:45,568 --> 00:08:47,570
Sorry I kept you
so long.

97
00:08:47,614 --> 00:08:49,616
 Sit up here 
and let me have 
a look at you.

98
00:08:56,013 --> 00:08:58,407
You don't recall having
a fall of any kind?

99
00:08:58,450 --> 00:09:00,148
No.

100
00:09:00,191 --> 00:09:02,280
Any double vision?

101
00:09:02,324 --> 00:09:04,892
- No.
- Follow my finger.

102
00:09:04,935 --> 00:09:07,111
Any tiny lights
when you look to the side?

103
00:09:07,155 --> 00:09:09,461
- No.
- What's my name?

104
00:09:09,505 --> 00:09:11,463
- Dr. Melloff.
- Good.

105
00:09:11,507 --> 00:09:13,901
Hold your hands out
flat.

106
00:09:13,944 --> 00:09:15,816
Don't let me
push them down.

107
00:09:15,859 --> 00:09:17,861
Good.

108
00:09:17,905 --> 00:09:19,994
Well, the EEG
looks fine.

109
00:09:20,037 --> 00:09:22,823
The skull films don't show
any fractures.

110
00:09:22,866 --> 00:09:25,869
Difficulty sleeping?

111
00:09:25,913 --> 00:09:27,436
- No.
- Staying awake?

112
00:09:27,479 --> 00:09:29,177
No.

113
00:09:29,220 --> 00:09:31,483
So what do you
remember?

114
00:09:31,527 --> 00:09:33,268
Come on, do I have to
go through this again?

115
00:09:33,311 --> 00:09:35,575
I've already talked to
the police, two interns,
and a nurse.

116
00:09:35,618 --> 00:09:36,967
Isn't it in your report?

117
00:09:37,011 --> 00:09:38,926
Indulge me.

118
00:09:41,319 --> 00:09:43,713
I found myself
at the supermarket

119
00:09:43,757 --> 00:09:45,454
and I didn't know
what I was doing there,

120
00:09:45,497 --> 00:09:48,196
how I got there,
or who I was.

121
00:09:48,239 --> 00:09:51,503
I was, um, alone

122
00:09:51,547 --> 00:09:53,854
and I had
no identification.

123
00:09:53,897 --> 00:09:55,203
I didn't know
what to do,

124
00:09:55,246 --> 00:09:58,685
so I-- I wandered around
for a few hours

125
00:09:58,728 --> 00:10:00,425
and then I checked
into a hotel.

126
00:10:00,469 --> 00:10:02,340
How'd you pay
for the hotel?

127
00:10:04,647 --> 00:10:08,390
I found some money
in the pocket of
my trench coat.

128
00:10:08,433 --> 00:10:10,914
Why didn't you go
to the police immediately?

129
00:10:13,047 --> 00:10:14,614
 Well, I was confused.

130
00:10:14,657 --> 00:10:16,920
[ stammering ]
I don't know.

131
00:10:16,964 --> 00:10:20,228
But you had no trouble
remembering the events
of the last 24 hours?

132
00:10:20,271 --> 00:10:22,578
- None.
- Could you
stand up for me?

133
00:10:25,712 --> 00:10:28,149
Close your eyes.
Balance on your right foot.

134
00:10:28,192 --> 00:10:30,760
Good.
What about current events?

135
00:10:30,804 --> 00:10:32,893
Do you know
who the president is?

136
00:10:32,936 --> 00:10:35,199
Well, I know who he is,
I just don't know if
I voted for him.

137
00:10:35,243 --> 00:10:37,114
Well, we don't have
all the blood work in,

138
00:10:37,158 --> 00:10:39,856
but I frankly don't think
we're gonna find
anything there.

139
00:10:41,771 --> 00:10:44,426
So you're telling me
I'm fine?

140
00:10:45,949 --> 00:10:48,473
- I'm delighted.
- You're not?

141
00:10:48,517 --> 00:10:51,085
No, Doctor.
I really need to know

142
00:10:51,128 --> 00:10:53,348
that there's a reason
I can't remember anything

143
00:10:53,391 --> 00:10:54,784
prior to yesterday.

144
00:10:54,828 --> 00:10:56,568
 There's a reason. 
What's my name?

145
00:10:56,612 --> 00:10:59,441
Dr. Melloff!
And why do you
keep asking me that?

146
00:10:59,484 --> 00:11:01,530
I don't have any problem
remembering other
people's names,

147
00:11:01,573 --> 00:11:03,619
only my own.

148
00:11:03,663 --> 00:11:05,752
Do you have a short fuse?

149
00:11:05,795 --> 00:11:07,362
How would I know?

150
00:11:11,453 --> 00:11:15,065
 [ chatter on P.A. ]

151
00:11:15,109 --> 00:11:16,893
Am I crazy?

152
00:11:16,937 --> 00:11:18,503
No.

153
00:11:18,547 --> 00:11:20,723
I think what we're
looking at here

154
00:11:20,767 --> 00:11:23,595
is acute
nonpsychotic syndrome.

155
00:11:23,639 --> 00:11:26,555
Well, that's very clear.

156
00:11:26,598 --> 00:11:28,731
In lay terms,
it works like this--

157
00:11:28,775 --> 00:11:32,300
everybody has a limit
to the tolerance of anxiety.

158
00:11:32,343 --> 00:11:35,042
And when that level is reached,
some people choose escape

159
00:11:35,085 --> 00:11:36,478
through a sudden loss
of memory.

160
00:11:36,521 --> 00:11:38,480
 It's called 
a fugue state.

161
00:11:38,523 --> 00:11:41,570
- So I'm nuts?
- On the contrary.

162
00:11:41,613 --> 00:11:43,093
In a way,
it's a healthy mechanism.

163
00:11:43,137 --> 00:11:45,661
When a life situation
becomes too stressful,

164
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:48,272
some of us deal with it
by not dealing with it,

165
00:11:48,316 --> 00:11:50,622
by escaping.
A form of self-preservation.

166
00:11:52,059 --> 00:11:54,017
Now, the good news
is that a fugue state

167
00:11:54,061 --> 00:11:55,584
usually disappears
within a few days,

168
00:11:55,627 --> 00:11:58,456
 weeks, months-- 
as quickly as it came.

169
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:00,415
I'll prescribe
some tranquilizers.

170
00:12:04,288 --> 00:12:05,942
And the bad news?

171
00:12:08,205 --> 00:12:09,467
You're going to
have to deal

172
00:12:09,511 --> 00:12:11,165
with the situation
that caused the trauma.

173
00:12:11,208 --> 00:12:12,732
 [ door opens ]

174
00:12:12,775 --> 00:12:15,125
Dr. Melloff,
may I see you
for a moment?

175
00:12:15,169 --> 00:12:16,779
I'll be right back.

176
00:12:24,265 --> 00:12:25,657
Dr. Melloff: 
Do you recognize this man?

177
00:12:31,663 --> 00:12:33,491
Well, that's Jane.

178
00:12:33,535 --> 00:12:35,755
That's my wife.

179
00:12:39,062 --> 00:12:41,325
Jane: 
When did you say 
we got married?

180
00:12:41,369 --> 00:12:43,719
Man: 
August 18th, 1982.

181
00:12:43,763 --> 00:12:46,330
 It's right there 
in the marriage 
certificate.

182
00:12:46,374 --> 00:12:48,506
Where is this?

183
00:12:48,550 --> 00:12:50,770
That's St. Thomas,
Christmas.

184
00:12:50,813 --> 00:12:52,510
Our first vacation.

185
00:12:52,554 --> 00:12:55,296
I had just finished
my surgical residency.

186
00:12:55,339 --> 00:12:57,864
Are you
at City General, too?

187
00:12:57,907 --> 00:12:59,779
No. I have
privileges there,

188
00:12:59,822 --> 00:13:02,433
but I'm Chief
of Pediatric Surgery

189
00:13:02,477 --> 00:13:04,218
at Jefferson Memorial.

190
00:13:07,743 --> 00:13:10,180
Where's
my wedding band?

191
00:13:12,879 --> 00:13:14,663
Your wedding band.

192
00:13:14,706 --> 00:13:17,405
You went into
a ladies' room
of a restaurant

193
00:13:17,448 --> 00:13:19,233
and went to put cream
in your hands or something.

194
00:13:19,276 --> 00:13:21,061
It slipped
down the drain.

195
00:13:21,104 --> 00:13:23,846
[ chuckles ]
You drove the manager crazy

196
00:13:23,890 --> 00:13:25,108
having him tear
all the plumbing apart.

197
00:13:25,152 --> 00:13:27,067
We never found it.

198
00:13:27,110 --> 00:13:31,114
I promised to replace it,
but I'm sorry. I forgot.

199
00:13:31,158 --> 00:13:33,334
Huh, you'd be amazed

200
00:13:33,377 --> 00:13:34,988
at the things
you can forget.

201
00:13:48,610 --> 00:13:50,612
 [ engine turns off ]

202
00:13:53,310 --> 00:13:56,096
No, wait. Please.

203
00:13:59,882 --> 00:14:01,579
[ sighs ]
Okay.

204
00:14:02,885 --> 00:14:05,192
How did you find me
at the hospital?

205
00:14:07,324 --> 00:14:10,110
You were on your way
to San Diego to visit
your brother Tom.

206
00:14:10,153 --> 00:14:12,460
I called to make sure
you got there safely

207
00:14:12,503 --> 00:14:14,027
and he said
you never made it.

208
00:14:14,070 --> 00:14:16,943
I got worried,
I called the police,

209
00:14:16,986 --> 00:14:18,770
and they said that they'd
just brought a woman in

210
00:14:18,814 --> 00:14:20,685
to City General
that was amnesiac.

211
00:14:20,729 --> 00:14:23,427
She matched
your description.

212
00:14:23,471 --> 00:14:26,256
Jane's voice: 
Okay, it sounds possible.

213
00:14:26,300 --> 00:14:30,347
Jane, you-- you--
don't push yourself
trying to remember.

214
00:14:30,391 --> 00:14:33,742
Dr. Melloff said
it's all gonna come back,

215
00:14:33,785 --> 00:14:36,919
- but you have to relax.
- Right.

216
00:14:36,963 --> 00:14:39,487
I know it must be
strange, you know,

217
00:14:39,530 --> 00:14:42,272
all of this
and particularly me,

218
00:14:42,316 --> 00:14:45,928
but...
I wanna say this

219
00:14:45,972 --> 00:14:49,062
and I'm not gonna say it again
until you're ready to hear it.

220
00:14:49,105 --> 00:14:51,107
 I love you.

221
00:14:51,151 --> 00:14:53,327
 We have 
a great life together.

222
00:14:53,370 --> 00:14:55,677
We're gonna get it back.

223
00:14:55,720 --> 00:14:58,810
 [ car door opens, 
closes ]

224
00:14:58,854 --> 00:15:02,205
Jane's voice: 
At least I have good taste.

225
00:15:08,951 --> 00:15:10,300
You okay?

226
00:15:11,432 --> 00:15:13,608
One brother,
no sisters?

227
00:15:13,651 --> 00:15:16,089
And your father died
when you were 11

228
00:15:16,132 --> 00:15:17,568
and you were very close
to your mother.

229
00:15:17,612 --> 00:15:19,309
- Were?
- Are.

230
00:15:19,353 --> 00:15:21,442
- You said "were."
- Let's wait on this.

231
00:15:21,485 --> 00:15:23,357
Is she dead?

232
00:15:23,400 --> 00:15:26,012
[ sighs ]
She died in
an accident last year.

233
00:15:26,055 --> 00:15:28,057
She was driving your car.

234
00:15:28,101 --> 00:15:30,799
Some guy ran a light.

235
00:15:30,842 --> 00:15:32,366
She died instantly.

236
00:15:33,584 --> 00:15:34,803
I'm sorry.

237
00:15:36,109 --> 00:15:37,937
Well, come on.
Let's go in.

238
00:15:41,462 --> 00:15:43,159
Woman: 
Hi, Michael.

239
00:15:43,203 --> 00:15:44,291
 Jane.

240
00:15:46,510 --> 00:15:49,861
- Who's that?
- That's Carole Garson.
She's a good friend.

241
00:15:49,905 --> 00:15:51,863
 She's lived over there 
almost as long as we have.

242
00:15:55,215 --> 00:15:57,521
She's going through
a rough time right now.

243
00:15:57,565 --> 00:16:00,133
Her husband Daniel
moved out a few months ago.

244
00:16:00,176 --> 00:16:02,004
Left her alone
with two teenagers.

245
00:16:02,048 --> 00:16:03,223
Her father
is going senile.

246
00:16:17,324 --> 00:16:19,369
 [ door closes ]

247
00:16:19,413 --> 00:16:22,242
[ scoffs ]
I gather I wasn't modest.

248
00:16:22,285 --> 00:16:24,026
Oh, I had that done.

249
00:16:24,070 --> 00:16:27,029
 You never liked it, 
but I love it.

250
00:16:36,734 --> 00:16:38,998
Well, here's
a tough one.

251
00:16:40,651 --> 00:16:42,610
Do we have
any children?

252
00:16:42,653 --> 00:16:44,394
Yes.

253
00:16:44,438 --> 00:16:47,006
A daughter, Amy.

254
00:16:47,049 --> 00:16:49,051
Seven.

255
00:16:49,095 --> 00:16:51,053
Jane:
Where is she?

256
00:16:51,097 --> 00:16:53,186
Michael: 
She's staying 
with my parents.

257
00:16:53,229 --> 00:16:55,492
 I think we ought to 
let her stay there 
for a while

258
00:16:55,536 --> 00:16:58,887
until, you know--
until this is over.

259
00:17:06,112 --> 00:17:08,897
The doctor said
you shouldn't actively
try to remember things.

260
00:17:08,940 --> 00:17:10,507
Why not?

261
00:17:10,551 --> 00:17:12,074
You know,
I keep thinking if I--

262
00:17:12,118 --> 00:17:13,945
if I look at something,

263
00:17:13,989 --> 00:17:17,297
[ stammering ]
then I might think
of something

264
00:17:17,340 --> 00:17:18,907
 and it'll all come back.

265
00:17:24,391 --> 00:17:26,741
I can dress
and undress myself.

266
00:17:28,003 --> 00:17:29,526
[ chuckles ]

267
00:17:29,570 --> 00:17:30,745
I'm hovering, aren't I?

268
00:17:30,788 --> 00:17:32,616
All right, look,

269
00:17:32,660 --> 00:17:35,315
I'm gonna sleep
in the guest room
for a couple of days

270
00:17:35,358 --> 00:17:36,925
until you feel
a little more comfortable.

271
00:17:36,968 --> 00:17:38,405
Thank you.

272
00:17:38,448 --> 00:17:40,842
I just--

273
00:17:40,885 --> 00:17:43,105
thank you.

274
00:17:43,149 --> 00:17:45,716
Also, I've, uh--

275
00:17:45,760 --> 00:17:47,936
I've hired a woman named
Paula Marinelli

276
00:17:47,979 --> 00:17:50,721
to help out
while I'm at the office.

277
00:17:50,765 --> 00:17:53,202
What's that?

278
00:17:53,246 --> 00:17:55,813
[ chuckles ]
You've always hated
taking medicine,

279
00:17:55,857 --> 00:17:59,252
but, uh, these are my old
tranquilizers

280
00:17:59,295 --> 00:18:00,775
that Dr. Melloff
prescribed.

281
00:18:00,818 --> 00:18:03,299
You take one of these
three times a day.

282
00:18:03,343 --> 00:18:05,432
 I'll get some water.

283
00:18:08,261 --> 00:18:12,047
- Tell me about our friends.
- [ water running ]

284
00:18:12,091 --> 00:18:14,223
 You wondering 
if there's any more 
of our favorites?

285
00:18:14,267 --> 00:18:16,921
Jane's voice: 
Rutherford.

286
00:18:16,965 --> 00:18:20,011
Michael: 
Well, there's Peter 
and Sarah Tanner.

287
00:18:20,055 --> 00:18:22,057
 Tanner?

288
00:18:23,928 --> 00:18:25,191
They're not in here.

289
00:18:25,234 --> 00:18:26,670
Well, check "S"
for Sarah

290
00:18:26,714 --> 00:18:28,585
or "B" for best friend

291
00:18:28,629 --> 00:18:30,109
or I don't know.

292
00:18:30,152 --> 00:18:32,633
You have your own weird
little Dewey Decimal System.

293
00:18:35,592 --> 00:18:37,290
Okay, here they are.

294
00:18:39,379 --> 00:18:41,903
Do we know anyone
named Pat?

295
00:18:43,600 --> 00:18:45,863
No. Pat, no.
Why?

296
00:18:45,907 --> 00:18:47,387
Why, does that name
mean something?

297
00:18:49,128 --> 00:18:51,434
No, it's just a--
just a name.

298
00:18:54,350 --> 00:18:55,873
What is it?
What are you thinking?

299
00:18:58,833 --> 00:19:00,617
Nothing.

300
00:19:02,228 --> 00:19:04,360
[ sighs ]
Jane.

301
00:19:04,404 --> 00:19:06,884
Jane, listen.

302
00:19:06,928 --> 00:19:09,104
The only way this thing
is gonna get fixed

303
00:19:09,148 --> 00:19:11,237
is if you take this

304
00:19:11,280 --> 00:19:13,543
and you totally relax.

305
00:19:21,247 --> 00:19:22,683
Okay.

306
00:19:24,554 --> 00:19:25,773
That's a girl.

307
00:19:25,816 --> 00:19:27,514
All right,
you'll sleep.

308
00:19:27,557 --> 00:19:30,081
Absolutely no stress.

309
00:19:31,605 --> 00:19:33,650
What happened?

310
00:19:35,478 --> 00:19:38,960
Oh, that's the hazards
of pediatrics.

311
00:19:39,003 --> 00:19:42,311
One of the kids in the office
slammed me in the head
with a metal plane.

312
00:19:53,583 --> 00:19:55,455
 [ birds chirping ]

313
00:19:58,240 --> 00:20:00,286
[ sighs ]

314
00:20:10,426 --> 00:20:12,559
 [ dog barking ]

315
00:20:18,434 --> 00:20:20,175
Hi.

316
00:20:20,219 --> 00:20:21,742
I'm Paula Marinelli.

317
00:20:21,785 --> 00:20:23,657
Dr. Ravenson
was supposed to tell you.

318
00:20:23,700 --> 00:20:26,181
Oh, he did.
I forgot.

319
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:28,139
Is-- is he still asleep?

320
00:20:28,183 --> 00:20:30,533
Oh, no. He had surgery
early this morning.

321
00:20:30,577 --> 00:20:32,579
 Are you hungry?

322
00:20:32,622 --> 00:20:34,320
I could bring you up
some breakfast.

323
00:20:34,363 --> 00:20:36,887
I'd rather eat
in the kitchen.

324
00:20:36,931 --> 00:20:40,413
The doctor wants you
to get as much rest
as possible.

325
00:20:40,456 --> 00:20:43,807
Well, I think
I can make it downstairs.

326
00:20:54,296 --> 00:20:57,125
So how did my husband
come to hire you?

327
00:20:57,168 --> 00:20:59,432
I met him
at the hospital.

328
00:20:59,475 --> 00:21:01,303
He operated
on my little girl.

329
00:21:01,347 --> 00:21:03,349
What was wrong with her?

330
00:21:03,392 --> 00:21:05,612
Spinal aneurysm.

331
00:21:05,655 --> 00:21:08,658
Dr. Ravenson operated
for eight hours.

332
00:21:08,702 --> 00:21:10,660
She would've died
without him.

333
00:21:10,704 --> 00:21:12,619
I'm sorry.

334
00:21:15,012 --> 00:21:16,971
Where is she
while you're working?

335
00:21:17,014 --> 00:21:18,538
My mother
looks after her.

336
00:21:18,581 --> 00:21:21,932
[ scoffs ]
So you can look after me?

337
00:21:21,976 --> 00:21:24,283
I'm happy to do it.

338
00:21:26,546 --> 00:21:29,984
Well, in a day or two,
I should be able to
manage by myself.

339
00:21:30,027 --> 00:21:32,291
Oh, no.

340
00:21:32,334 --> 00:21:35,511
I am here till everything's
back to order.

341
00:21:35,555 --> 00:21:37,470
That's very nice of you.

342
00:21:37,513 --> 00:21:41,212
 I could never 
repay Dr. Ravenson 
for what he did.

343
00:21:41,256 --> 00:21:43,780
 I was on welfare 
when Christina 
needed the surgery

344
00:21:43,824 --> 00:21:44,999
and I couldn't pay.

345
00:21:45,042 --> 00:21:46,740
But he operated anyway

346
00:21:46,783 --> 00:21:48,959
and he offered me a job.

347
00:21:49,003 --> 00:21:51,353
And your husband?

348
00:21:51,397 --> 00:21:53,573
I was never married.

349
00:21:53,616 --> 00:21:55,879
- Sorry.
- I'm not.

350
00:21:55,923 --> 00:21:58,360
Very few men
are like your husband.

351
00:21:58,404 --> 00:22:00,580
- Mm.
- Are you all done?

352
00:22:05,454 --> 00:22:07,717
Jane's voice: 
She's in love with Michael.

353
00:22:17,379 --> 00:22:19,381
Jane's voice: 
Oh, Amy, do you miss me?

354
00:22:22,253 --> 00:22:24,386
Come on.
Medication and nap.

355
00:22:24,430 --> 00:22:27,563
- But I just got up.
- That was hours ago.

356
00:22:39,053 --> 00:22:40,794
Here you go.

357
00:22:40,837 --> 00:22:42,404
Oh, I don't want
any more pills.

358
00:22:42,448 --> 00:22:44,058
They make me feel
like I'm underwater.

359
00:22:44,101 --> 00:22:45,407
Please take them.

360
00:22:45,451 --> 00:22:47,191
Dr. Ravenson
thinks it's important.

361
00:22:57,941 --> 00:22:59,943
Thank you.

362
00:23:09,562 --> 00:23:13,653
I take it every Wednesday.
It's a great class to do.

363
00:23:13,696 --> 00:23:15,350
Oh, I'll take
the class.

364
00:23:15,394 --> 00:23:17,657
Okay.
All right.

365
00:23:17,700 --> 00:23:19,615
- [ horn honks ]
- Watch out.

366
00:23:19,659 --> 00:23:22,096
Turn on your lights, jerk!

367
00:23:22,139 --> 00:23:23,880
- Shh!
- [ brakes screech ]

368
00:23:25,882 --> 00:23:28,668
Hey! Mind your own
damn business!

369
00:23:28,711 --> 00:23:31,061
- You mind yours!
- All right, come on.
Let's get out of here.

370
00:23:31,105 --> 00:23:32,498
Come on. Come on!

371
00:23:32,541 --> 00:23:34,891
 [ echoes ] 
You wanna get us killed?

372
00:23:36,937 --> 00:23:39,069
[ tires screeching ]

373
00:23:40,593 --> 00:23:42,290
[ both screaming ]

374
00:23:42,333 --> 00:23:44,945
 [ phone ringing ]

375
00:23:51,255 --> 00:23:54,128
- Hello?
- [ ringing continues ]

376
00:23:57,740 --> 00:23:59,699
Paula: 
Mrs. Ravenson 
isn't in right now.

377
00:23:59,742 --> 00:24:02,179
She's visiting her brother
for a few weeks.

378
00:24:02,223 --> 00:24:04,834
All right.
Thank you.

379
00:24:06,532 --> 00:24:09,012
- Who was that?
- I don't know.

380
00:24:09,056 --> 00:24:10,971
Some-- someone
named Sarah.

381
00:24:11,014 --> 00:24:14,061
Well, why did you say
I was visiting my brother?

382
00:24:14,104 --> 00:24:17,499
Well, Dr. Ravenson said
you shouldn't be disturbed
by phone calls right now.

383
00:24:17,543 --> 00:24:19,632
Well, what if I wanna talk
to that person?

384
00:24:19,675 --> 00:24:22,243
Wait till you get
your strength back.

385
00:24:22,286 --> 00:24:25,376
There's nothing wrong
with my strength.
It's my memory.

386
00:24:25,420 --> 00:24:30,164
Then what's the point
of talking with someone
you can't remember?

387
00:24:33,123 --> 00:24:36,997
And then this maniac
starts backing up full speed

388
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:39,129
and tries to run us over.

389
00:24:39,173 --> 00:24:41,218
That's not a dream.

390
00:24:41,262 --> 00:24:42,742
It really happened.

391
00:24:44,221 --> 00:24:46,485
I've always had
this violent temper.

392
00:24:46,528 --> 00:24:48,530
I was always afraid
it was gonna get you
into trouble.

393
00:24:48,574 --> 00:24:51,272
 And this one night, 
it almost got you 
and Sarah killed.

394
00:24:51,315 --> 00:24:53,666
But I only told the guy
his lights were off.

395
00:24:53,709 --> 00:24:56,538
- He went berserk.
- Well, a lot of nuts
out there,

396
00:24:56,582 --> 00:24:58,932
but this is a good sign.

397
00:24:58,975 --> 00:25:02,196
It means that
pieces of your memory
are coming back.

398
00:25:03,502 --> 00:25:05,373
But, Michael,
these pills.

399
00:25:05,416 --> 00:25:07,636
I feel so rotten.
I feel like I'm underwater.

400
00:25:07,680 --> 00:25:11,118
My mouth is dry,
I have bad dreams.

401
00:25:11,161 --> 00:25:13,076
Say no more.

402
00:25:19,039 --> 00:25:21,824
[ touch tones beeping ]

403
00:25:23,522 --> 00:25:25,175
 [ line ringing ]

404
00:25:25,219 --> 00:25:27,438
- Hello?
- Yeah, hi, Dr. Melloff.

405
00:25:27,482 --> 00:25:29,832
I'm sorry to
bother you so late.
This is Michael Ravenson.

406
00:25:29,876 --> 00:25:32,269
- Yes, Michael. 
How can I help?
- Uh, listen,

407
00:25:32,313 --> 00:25:34,489
Jane's having a problem
with the medication.

408
00:25:34,533 --> 00:25:37,927
 She's not so comfortable. 
What do you think's 
going on?

409
00:25:37,971 --> 00:25:41,583
- Is she sleeping?
- Yeah, well, that's
all she's doing.

410
00:25:41,627 --> 00:25:44,847
Dr. Melloff: 
It's not the medication. 
I think it's her system.

411
00:25:44,891 --> 00:25:47,589
 Michael, she has to understand 
it's going to take time.

412
00:25:47,633 --> 00:25:50,244
 The important thing 
is not to let her get upset.

413
00:25:50,287 --> 00:25:51,898
Michael: 
And that's it?

414
00:25:51,941 --> 00:25:53,987
 I think so for now.

415
00:25:54,030 --> 00:25:55,858
All right, thank you.

416
00:25:55,902 --> 00:25:57,947
 Okay, just call 
if you have any 
further problems.

417
00:25:57,991 --> 00:26:00,559
Will do. Night.

418
00:26:01,690 --> 00:26:02,691
[ sighs ]

419
00:26:05,564 --> 00:26:08,262
- [ muffled music playing ]
- [ doorbell rings ]

420
00:26:12,614 --> 00:26:14,137
- Hi.
- Hi.

421
00:26:14,181 --> 00:26:15,878
Um, this is
a little clumsy.

422
00:26:15,922 --> 00:26:18,707
Um, Michael told me
we were friends

423
00:26:18,751 --> 00:26:22,189
and I needed
to talk to someone.

424
00:26:22,232 --> 00:26:23,973
- I escaped.
- From what?

425
00:26:24,017 --> 00:26:26,062
- Paula,
- Oh.

426
00:26:26,106 --> 00:26:28,543
the woman Michael hired
to babysit me.

427
00:26:28,587 --> 00:26:30,110
Uh-huh.

428
00:26:30,153 --> 00:26:33,635
You take, uh, cream,
no sugar, right?

429
00:26:33,679 --> 00:26:35,811
Huh, I don't know.

430
00:26:35,855 --> 00:26:38,553
You really can't
remember anything?

431
00:26:38,597 --> 00:26:42,296
Well, neither can I,
but I can't blame mine
on trauma.

432
00:26:42,339 --> 00:26:44,646
I think you take cream.

433
00:26:47,867 --> 00:26:50,652
- Hey.
- Oh, hi, Mrs. Ravenson.

434
00:26:50,696 --> 00:26:52,393
- Hi.
- Hey, I'm out of here.

435
00:26:52,436 --> 00:26:54,482
Hold it, hold it.

436
00:26:54,525 --> 00:26:56,179
Aren't you supposed to
take your grandpa
for a walk first?

437
00:26:56,223 --> 00:26:58,747
- Mom, I'm late.
- You're late.

438
00:26:58,791 --> 00:27:00,923
- Yeah! Celine will do it.
- Carole: Oh, yeah, sure, 
Celine will do it.

439
00:27:00,967 --> 00:27:03,447
Do you see
Celine anywhere? Oh!

440
00:27:03,491 --> 00:27:05,972
This is my job.
My job is I'm supposed
to take care of everything

441
00:27:06,015 --> 00:27:07,277
because nobody else
can do anything.

442
00:27:07,321 --> 00:27:09,671
Do you see Celine?
I don't see Celine.

443
00:27:09,715 --> 00:27:11,673
- No, look, if this
isn't a good time, I can--
- Oh, please, Jane,

444
00:27:11,717 --> 00:27:13,719
- there's no good time.
- I'm sorry.

445
00:27:13,762 --> 00:27:15,938
- I'm-- I'm really sorry.
- Are you?

446
00:27:17,157 --> 00:27:18,985
Do you remember Daniel?

447
00:27:19,028 --> 00:27:21,378
My soon-to-be
ex-husband Daniel?

448
00:27:21,422 --> 00:27:23,554
 [ clock ticking ]

449
00:27:23,598 --> 00:27:25,948
[ scoffs ]
Wow, that's amazing.

450
00:27:25,992 --> 00:27:28,821
You used to
go running with him
every morning.

451
00:27:28,864 --> 00:27:30,518
Oh, Michael told me.

452
00:27:30,561 --> 00:27:32,999
You're a very
lucky woman, Jane.

453
00:27:33,042 --> 00:27:35,436
You're married
to the perfect man.

454
00:27:35,479 --> 00:27:38,178
- That seems so...
- [ chuckles ]

455
00:27:38,221 --> 00:27:41,529
In fact, you don't even know
how perfect, do you?

456
00:27:41,572 --> 00:27:43,270
[ chuckles ]

457
00:27:43,313 --> 00:27:45,707
- [ doorbell rings ]
- What's that supposed to mean?

458
00:27:45,751 --> 00:27:47,927
Excuse me,
I have to get the door.

459
00:27:47,970 --> 00:27:50,146
Probably not as chaotic
over at your house.

460
00:27:50,190 --> 00:27:52,148
- [ knocking, 
doorbell ringing ]
- Okay, I'm coming!

461
00:27:52,192 --> 00:27:54,020
- [ door opens ]
- Carole: Oh, hi.

462
00:27:54,063 --> 00:27:56,587
- Paula: Is Jane here?
- Uh, yes, actually, she is.

463
00:27:56,631 --> 00:27:58,677
- [ door closes ]
- [ sighs ]

464
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:00,679
- I think this must be
your keeper.
- Where have you been?

465
00:28:00,722 --> 00:28:02,376
You don't even tell me
you're leaving the house.

466
00:28:02,419 --> 00:28:04,378
I go to give you
your medication,
you're not there.

467
00:28:04,421 --> 00:28:05,814
I didn't think I needed
to ask permission--

468
00:28:05,858 --> 00:28:07,337
Dr. Ravenson trusts me
to take care of you.

469
00:28:07,381 --> 00:28:08,730
Didn't you think
I'd be frightened?

470
00:28:08,774 --> 00:28:10,819
 I've been up and down 
the street.

471
00:28:10,863 --> 00:28:12,168
- Been looking 
for you everywhere!
- Okay, okay, okay.

472
00:28:12,212 --> 00:28:13,692
Paula, I'm sorry.

473
00:28:16,956 --> 00:28:18,740
Thanks for the coffee.

474
00:28:18,784 --> 00:28:20,350
Yeah, sure.

475
00:28:21,525 --> 00:28:23,571
 [ door opens ]

476
00:28:23,614 --> 00:28:25,181
 [ door closes ]

477
00:28:25,225 --> 00:28:27,183
- [ dog barking ]
- [ birds chirping ]

478
00:28:50,250 --> 00:28:52,731
Amy's voice: 
Mommy, hurry! 
Come and get me!

479
00:28:52,774 --> 00:28:54,645
- Amy, Amy,
just calm down, sweetheart.
- Mommy, where are you?

480
00:28:54,689 --> 00:28:57,823
Just calm down
and tell Mommy exactly
where you are, okay?

481
00:28:57,866 --> 00:28:59,607
- I can't, Mommy!
Help me, Mommy!
- Just calm down. Shh.

482
00:28:59,650 --> 00:29:02,088
- Help me!
- Mommy will be there.

483
00:29:02,131 --> 00:29:03,916
- Please help, Mommy!
- Don't worry, honey.
Mommy will be there.

484
00:29:03,959 --> 00:29:05,439
- Mommy loves you. Calm down.
- Help me! Please help me!

485
00:29:05,482 --> 00:29:08,572
Amy? Amy?!

486
00:29:08,616 --> 00:29:11,750
[ echoes ]
You just missed her.
Check the playground.

487
00:29:13,882 --> 00:29:15,754
Amy!

488
00:29:15,797 --> 00:29:17,190
Amy?

489
00:29:17,233 --> 00:29:19,627
- [ horn honks ]
- [ tires screech ]

490
00:29:19,670 --> 00:29:21,803
Come on, the gas pedal,
you idiot!

491
00:29:21,847 --> 00:29:23,587
- The long, skinny one 
on the right!
- [ horn honks ]

492
00:29:23,631 --> 00:29:25,415
- Don't get out of your car!
- [ car door closes ]

493
00:29:25,459 --> 00:29:28,767
Temper, temper.
You don't wanna get
involved in an accident.

494
00:29:31,639 --> 00:29:33,554
- Stop!
- Mommy!

495
00:29:33,597 --> 00:29:35,730
No!
[ gasps ]

496
00:29:35,774 --> 00:29:38,472
[ pants ]
Oh.

497
00:29:45,871 --> 00:29:47,394
Amy.

498
00:29:55,141 --> 00:29:56,838
It's Mommy.

499
00:29:56,882 --> 00:30:00,146
- It's Mommy.
- [ screams ] Mommy! Mommy!

500
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:03,845
- [ cries ]
- It's all right.

501
00:30:03,889 --> 00:30:06,065
There's nothing
to be afraid of.

502
00:30:06,108 --> 00:30:08,807
 Mommy told you 
not to go upstairs.

503
00:30:08,850 --> 00:30:11,592
I'm sorry
if she disturbed you.

504
00:30:11,635 --> 00:30:14,290
 My mother 
had to go to the doctor, 
